<heading id="D0AE81A1FFC5FFA823FA8AD2FDD7C1D1" box="[151,631,723,748]" fontSize="10" level="2" pageId="23" pageNumber="252" reason="2">
<taxonomicName id="4C594D4EFFC5FFA823FA8AD2FDD7C1D1" authority="Sueur &amp; Puissant, 2007" authorityName="Sueur &amp; Puissant" authorityYear="2007" box="[151,631,723,748]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadidae" genus="Cicadetta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="252" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cantilatrix">
<emphasis id="B92DEADFFFC5FFA823FA8AD2FED8C1D6" bold="true" box="[151,376,724,748]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="252">Cicadetta cantilatrix</emphasis>
Sueur &amp;Puissant, 2007
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE636CDFFC5FFA8238E8AF5FC30C031" blockId="23.[151,912,723,779]" box="[227,912,755,779]" pageId="23" pageNumber="252">
German common name: Honigader-Bergzikade (
<bibRefCitation id="EFC84B3CFFC5FFA821838AF5FC29C031" author="HERTACH, T." box="[750,905,755,779]" pageId="23" pageNumber="252" refId="ref17089" refString="HERTACH, T. 2010. Pechader-Bergzikade (Cicadetta montana) (p. 183). In: I NEICHEN, S. &amp; RUCKSTUHL, M. (eds). Stadtfauna - 600 Tierarten der Stadt Zurich. Haupt Verlag Bern, Stuttgart, Wien, 446 pp." type="book" year="2010">Hertach, 2010</bibRefCitation>
)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3436546FFC5FFA8238E8B18FE11C04C" pageId="23" pageNumber="252" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BE636CDFFC5FFA8238E8B18FE11C04C" blockId="23.[151,1073,798,886]" pageId="23" pageNumber="252">
<taxonomicName id="4C594D4EFFC5FFA8238E8B18FE63C00C" authorityName="Sueur &amp; Puissant" authorityYear="2007" box="[227,451,798,822]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadidae" genus="Cicadetta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="252" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cantilatrix">
<emphasis id="B92DEADFFFC5FFA8238E8B18FE63C00C" box="[227,451,798,822]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="252">Cicadetta cantilatrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can often be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="4C594D4EFFC5FFA820598B19FC13C00C" baseAuthorityName="Scopoli" baseAuthorityYear="1772" box="[820,947,799,822]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadidae" genus="Cicadetta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="252" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="montana">
<emphasis id="B92DEADFFFC5FFA820598B19FC13C00C" box="[820,947,799,822]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="252">C. montana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A21E57A4FFC5FFA820D08B19FC59C00C" box="[957,1017,798,822]" pageId="23" pageNumber="252" sensu="stricto">s. str.</taxonomicNameLabel>
by a yellow to brown colouration of the basal venation of the fore wing (“Honigader” = honey coloured venation).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3436546FFC5FFA823FA8B97FE28C093" box="[151,392,913,937]" pageId="23" pageNumber="252" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BE636CDFFC5FFA823FA8B97FE28C093" blockId="23.[151,1074,913,1545]" box="[151,392,913,937]" pageId="23" pageNumber="252">DISTRIBUTION (Fig. 9)</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3436546FFC5FFA8238E8BB7FC24C533" pageId="23" pageNumber="252" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="8BE636CDFFC5FFA8238E8BB7FBB1C793" blockId="23.[151,1074,913,1545]" pageId="23" pageNumber="252">
<taxonomicName id="4C594D4EFFC5FFA8238E8BB7FECEC0F3" authorityName="Sueur &amp; Puissant" authorityYear="2007" box="[227,366,945,969]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadidae" genus="Cicadetta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="252" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cantilatrix">
<emphasis id="B92DEADFFFC5FFA8238E8BB7FECEC0F3" box="[227,366,945,969]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="252">C. cantilatrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described very recently and separated from 
<taxonomicName id="4C594D4EFFC5FFA820028BB7FBB1C0F3" authorityName="Puissant &amp; Boulard" authorityYear="2000" box="[879,1041,945,969]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadidae" genus="Cicadetta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="252" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cerdaniensis">
<emphasis id="B92DEADFFFC5FFA820028BB7FBB1C0F3" box="[879,1041,945,969]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="252">C. cerdaniensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by acoustic characters (Sueur &amp; Puissant, 2007a). For the acoustic description Sueur &amp; Puissant integrated recordings from 
<collectingCountry id="F34E765DFFC5FFA821768BF7FD38C733" box="[539,664,1009,1033]" name="Switzerland" pageId="23" pageNumber="252">Switzerland</collectingCountry>
(Martigny-Combe, VS), but the 
<typeStatus id="54E2886FFFC5FFA820978BF7FF64C713" pageId="23" pageNumber="252">holotype</typeStatus>
and 
<typeStatus id="54E2886FFFC5FFA823958C17FEF2C713" box="[248,338,1041,1065]" pageId="23" pageNumber="252">paratype</typeStatus>
were collected in 
<collectingCountry id="F34E765DFFC5FFA821798C17FDFFC713" box="[532,607,1041,1065]" name="France" pageId="23" pageNumber="252">France</collectingCountry>
. The taxon has been discussed critically due to intermediary song patterns observed several times in northern 
<collectingCountry id="F34E765DFFC5FFA820278C37FC67C773" box="[842,967,1073,1097]" name="Switzerland" pageId="23" pageNumber="252">Switzerland</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFC84B3CFFC5FFA820BB8C37FF70C753" author="HERTACH, T." pageId="23" pageNumber="252" pagination="37 - 61" refId="ref17011" refString="HERTACH, T. 2007. Three species instead of only one: Distribution and ecology of the Cicadetta montana species complex (Hemiptera: Cicadoidea) in Switzerland. Mitteilungen der Schweizerischen Entomologischen Gesellschaft 80: 37 - 61." type="journal article" year="2007">Hertach, 2007</bibRefCitation>
). These intermediary song patterns are now interpreted as courtship songs of 
<taxonomicName id="4C594D4EFFC5FFA823FA8C77FE86C7B3" authorityName="Sueur &amp; Puissant" authorityYear="2007" box="[151,294,1137,1161]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadidae" genus="Cicadetta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="252" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cantilatrix">
<emphasis id="B92DEADFFFC5FFA823FA8C77FE86C7B3" box="[151,294,1137,1161]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="252">C. cantilatrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFC84B3CFFC5FFA8225A8C77FE57C7B3" author="TRILAR, T. &amp; OGALA, M. &amp; ZWEDO, J." box="[311,503,1137,1161]" pageId="23" pageNumber="252" pagination="313 - 320" refId="ref19602" refString="TRILAR, T., G OGALA, M. &amp; S ZWEDO, J. 2006. Pyrenean Mountain Cicada Cicadetta cerdaniensis Puissant &amp; Boulard (Hemiptera: Cicadomorpha: Cicadidae) found in Poland. Polskie Pismo Entomologiczne 75 (2): 313 - 320." type="journal article" year="2006">
Trilar 
<emphasis id="B92DEADFFFC5FFA822138C74FE16C7B3" box="[382,438,1137,1161]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="252">et al.</emphasis>
,2006
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC84B3CFFC5FFA821688C77FD3EC7B3" author="HERTACH, T." box="[517,670,1137,1161]" pageId="23" pageNumber="252" pagination="25 - 40" refId="ref17141" refString="HERTACH, T. 2011. Spectacular song pattern from the Sicilian Mountains: The new cicada species Cicadetta anapaistica sp. n. (Hemiptera: Cicadidae). Zootaxa 2771: 25 - 40." type="journal article" year="2011">Hertach, 2011</bibRefCitation>
) which are very close to the calling songs of 
<taxonomicName id="4C594D4EFFC5FFA8239A8C97FE3AC793" authorityName="Puissant &amp; Boulard" authorityYear="2000" box="[247,410,1169,1193]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadidae" genus="Cicadetta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="252" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cerdaniensis">
<emphasis id="B92DEADFFFC5FFA8239A8C97FE3AC793" box="[247,410,1169,1193]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="252">C. cerdaniensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.Therefore, 
<taxonomicName id="4C594D4EFFC5FFA821708C97FD09C793" authorityName="Sueur &amp; Puissant" authorityYear="2007" box="[541,681,1169,1193]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadidae" genus="Cicadetta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="252" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cantilatrix">
<emphasis id="B92DEADFFFC5FFA821708C97FD09C793" box="[541,681,1169,1193]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="252">C. cantilatrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is avalid species (
<bibRefCitation id="EFC84B3CFFC5FFA820068C97FBA6C793" author="HERTACH, T." box="[875,1030,1169,1193]" pageId="23" pageNumber="252" pagination="25 - 40" refId="ref17141" refString="HERTACH, T. 2011. Spectacular song pattern from the Sicilian Mountains: The new cicada species Cicadetta anapaistica sp. n. (Hemiptera: Cicadidae). Zootaxa 2771: 25 - 40." type="journal article" year="2011">Hertach, 2011</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE636CDFFC5FFA8238E8CB7FC24C533" blockId="23.[151,1074,913,1545]" pageId="23" pageNumber="252">
It is possible that 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC84B3CFFC5FFA822F38CB7FD8DC7F3" author="BREMI, H." box="[414,557,1201,1225]" pageId="23" pageNumber="252" pagination="325 - 339" refId="ref15650" refString="BREMI, H. 1849. Uebersicht der schweizerischen Rhynchoten. Mittheilungen der Naturforschenden Gesellschaft in Zurich 34: 325 - 339." type="journal article" year="1849">Bremi (1849)</bibRefCitation>
and his German colleague Siebold already knew about this species. There is an older reference to a population in Diegten (BL, Jura Mountains; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC84B3CFFC5FFA8227E8CF7FE13C633" author="ARTMANN, G." box="[275,435,1265,1289]" pageId="23" pageNumber="252" pagination="190 - 192" refId="ref15340" refString="ARTMANN, G. 1987. Die fremdsprachige Bergzikade (Cicadetta montana peregrina). Mit - teilungen der Entomologischen Gesellschaft Basel 37 (4): 190 - 192." type="journal article" year="1987">Artmann, 1987</bibRefCitation>
) where the species is still present and frequent. 
<taxonomicName id="4C594D4EFFC5FFA820CB8CF7FB91C633" authorityName="Sueur &amp; Puissant" authorityYear="2007" box="[934,1073,1265,1289]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadidae" genus="Cicadetta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="252" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cantilatrix">
<emphasis id="B92DEADFFFC5FFA820CB8CF7FB91C633" box="[934,1073,1265,1289]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="252">C. cantilatrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is not rare in 
<collectingCountry id="F34E765DFFC5FFA822478D17FE07C613" box="[298,423,1297,1321]" name="Switzerland" pageId="23" pageNumber="252">Switzerland</collectingCountry>
and it is surprising that it was not detected earlier (
<bibRefCitation id="EFC84B3CFFC5FFA820BA8D17FF70C673" author="HERTACH, T." pageId="23" pageNumber="252" pagination="37 - 61" refId="ref17011" refString="HERTACH, T. 2007. Three species instead of only one: Distribution and ecology of the Cicadetta montana species complex (Hemiptera: Cicadoidea) in Switzerland. Mitteilungen der Schweizerischen Entomologischen Gesellschaft 80: 37 - 61." type="journal article" year="2007">Hertach, 2007</bibRefCitation>
). It is well distributed in the 
<collectingRegion id="499DF82FFFC5FFA822988D37FD81C673" box="[501,545,1329,1353]" country="Switzerland" name="Jura" pageId="23" pageNumber="252">Jura</collectingRegion>
Mountains including the Randen massif in the east and entering to the eastern part of the hilly Swiss Plateau. We have found 17 local populations solely in the 
<collectingRegion id="499DF82FFFC5FFA822F28D77FDFCC6B3" box="[415,604,1393,1417]" country="Switzerland" name="Aargau" pageId="23" pageNumber="252">Canton of Aargau</collectingRegion>
, some of them abundant. It also occurs quite regularly in the lower 
<collectingRegion id="499DF82FFFC5FFA822138D97FE1EC693" box="[382,446,1425,1449]" country="Switzerland" name="Valais" pageId="23" pageNumber="252">Valais</collectingRegion>
and in the Chablais (VD). The main distribution is split into two big disjunct metapopulations in 
<collectingCountry id="F34E765DFFC5FFA8215A8DB7FD14C6F3" box="[567,692,1457,1481]" name="Switzerland" pageId="23" pageNumber="252">Switzerland</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion id="499DF82FFFC5FFA821A58DB7FD55C6F3" box="[712,757,1457,1481]" country="Switzerland" name="Jura" pageId="23" pageNumber="252">Jura</collectingRegion>
and Chablais/ 
<collectingRegion id="499DF82FFFC5FFA820F68DB7FC7EC6F3" box="[923,990,1457,1481]" country="Switzerland" name="Valais" pageId="23" pageNumber="252">Valais</collectingRegion>
). Additionally,there are three supposedly isolated local populations: Immenberg(TG, discovered by Keist), Uetliberg(ZH, discovered by Rey) and Epesses (VD).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3436546FFC5FFA823FA8E27FB84C543" pageId="23" pageNumber="252" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8BE636CDFFC5FFA823FA8E27FE2AC50D" blockId="23.[151,1067,1569,1657]" box="[151,394,1569,1592]" pageId="23" pageNumber="252">ECOLOGY AND THREAT</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE636CDFFC5FFA8238E8E47FB84C543" blockId="23.[151,1067,1569,1657]" pageId="23" pageNumber="252">
<taxonomicName id="4C594D4EFFC5FFA8238E8E47FED7C563" authorityName="Sueur &amp; Puissant" authorityYear="2007" box="[227,375,1601,1625]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadidae" genus="Cicadetta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="252" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cantilatrix">
<emphasis id="B92DEADFFFC5FFA8238E8E47FED7C563" box="[227,375,1601,1625]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="252">C. cantilatrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is specialized on sparse Scots Pine forests with a grass-rich understorey on marl (= 
<emphasis id="B92DEADFFFC5FFA822F28E67FDE3C543" box="[415,579,1633,1657]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="252">Molinio-Pinion</emphasis>
,see Delarze &amp;Gonseth, 2008) and variable
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3436546FFCAFFA721548B6CFE2EC606" pageId="24" pageNumber="253" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BE636CDFFCAFFA721548B6CFC5EC0A4" blockId="24.[173,1022,874,926]" pageId="24" pageNumber="253">
FIG.9 Distribution map of 
<taxonomicName id="4C594D4EFFCAFFA7221F8B8EFD9AC0A4" authorityName="Sueur &amp; Puissant" authorityYear="2007" box="[370,570,904,926]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadidae" genus="Cicadetta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="253" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cantilatrix">
<emphasis id="B92DEADFFFCAFFA7221F8B8EFD9AC0A4" box="[370,570,904,926]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="253">Cicadetta cantilatrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
including solely acoustically checked records.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE636CDFFCAFFA723E58BC2FCD8C746" blockId="24.[136,1059,964,1340]" pageId="24" pageNumber="253">
edges of the forest along extensively used semidry meadows normally with Upright Brome (
<emphasis id="B92DEADFFFCAFFA7238F8BE3FE29C0C6" box="[226,393,997,1020]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="253">Bromus erectus</emphasis>
)(= 
<emphasis id="B92DEADFFFCAFFA722D68BE2FDEEC0C6" box="[443,590,996,1020]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="253">Mesobromion</emphasis>
,see Delarze &amp;Gonseth, 2008) in the 
<collectingRegion id="499DF82FFFCAFFA720848BE3FBB5C0C6" box="[1001,1045,997,1020]" country="Switzerland" name="Jura" pageId="24" pageNumber="253">Jura</collectingRegion>
Mountains and in the Chablais and on sparse woods with Downy Oak (
<taxonomicName id="4C594D4EFFCAFFA720A48C03FF56C706" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="24" pageNumber="253" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pubescens">
<emphasis id="B92DEADFFFCAFFA720A48C03FF56C706" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="253">Quercus pubescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
)in the 
<collectingRegion id="499DF82FFFCAFFA7222F8C22FE23C706" box="[322,387,1060,1084]" country="Switzerland" name="Valais" pageId="24" pageNumber="253">Valais</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFC84B3CFFCAFFA722FF8C22FD90C706" author="HERTACH, T." box="[402,560,1060,1084]" pageId="24" pageNumber="253" pagination="37 - 61" refId="ref17011" refString="HERTACH, T. 2007. Three species instead of only one: Distribution and ecology of the Cicadetta montana species complex (Hemiptera: Cicadoidea) in Switzerland. Mitteilungen der Schweizerischen Entomologischen Gesellschaft 80: 37 - 61." type="journal article" year="2007">Hertach, 2007</bibRefCitation>
). In contrast to 
<taxonomicName id="4C594D4EFFCAFFA721B08C23FCFAC706" baseAuthorityName="Scopoli" baseAuthorityYear="1772" box="[733,858,1061,1084]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadidae" genus="Cicadetta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="253" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="montana">
<emphasis id="B92DEADFFFCAFFA721B08C23FCFAC706" box="[733,858,1061,1084]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="253">C. montana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
,it scarcely occurs on rocky cliffs and ridges. It is a stenoecious species whose abundance is often correlated with nature conservation measures and traditional land use.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE636CDFFCAFFA723B98C82FE2EC606" blockId="24.[136,1059,964,1340]" pageId="24" pageNumber="253">
Beyond 
<collectingCountry id="F34E765DFFCAFFA722408C82FE0FC7A6" box="[301,431,1156,1180]" name="Switzerland" pageId="24" pageNumber="253">Switzerland</collectingCountry>
, the distribution area is large, but acomparable abundance is not known. It therefore seems that the Swiss responsibility for its conservation is high. As in 
<taxonomicName id="4C594D4EFFCAFFA7226F8CC3FEDEC7E6" baseAuthorityName="Scopoli" baseAuthorityYear="1772" box="[258,382,1221,1244]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadidae" genus="Cicadetta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="253" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="montana">
<emphasis id="B92DEADFFFCAFFA7226F8CC3FEDEC7E6" box="[258,382,1221,1244]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="253">C. montana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A21E57A4FFCAFFA722E88CC3FE1FC7E6" box="[389,447,1221,1244]" pageId="24" pageNumber="253" sensu="stricto">s. str.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, it benefits from recent improvements of suitable habitats (
<bibRefCitation id="EFC84B3CFFCAFFA723E28CE2FE8CC7C6" author="HERTACH, T." box="[143,300,1252,1276]" pageId="24" pageNumber="253" pagination="37 - 61" refId="ref17011" refString="HERTACH, T. 2007. Three species instead of only one: Distribution and ecology of the Cicadetta montana species complex (Hemiptera: Cicadoidea) in Switzerland. Mitteilungen der Schweizerischen Entomologischen Gesellschaft 80: 37 - 61." type="journal article" year="2007">Hertach, 2007</bibRefCitation>
). The very active role of cantonal authorities in thinning out pine forests might create an important positive factor for the current frequency in the Cantons of 
<collectingRegion id="499DF82FFFCAFFA723E58D22FF76C606" box="[136,214,1316,1340]" country="Switzerland" name="Aargau" pageId="24" pageNumber="253">Aargau</collectingRegion>
and Basel-Land.
</paragraph>
